  <body>
    <section name="Requirements">
     <span class='shortdesc'>What do you need to run Hippo CMS?</span>

      <subsection name="Operating System">
      
      <blockquote>  
        <table>
         <tr>
          <td>Overall</td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/overall.png' alt='overall icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>
              Hippo CMS runs on all modern operating systems
              that run <a href='http://www.sun.com/'>Sun</a>'s 
              <span class='expires'>Java 6 (or 5)</span> 
              correctly.
    </td>
         </tr>


         <tr>
          <td>
           Tested
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/tested.png' alt='Tested icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>Hippo continuously tests Hippo CMS on 
  <a href='http://www.microsoft.com/windows/windows-xp/default.aspx'>Microsoft Windows XP</a>
   and Linux: 
  <a href='http://www.ubuntu.com/'>Ubuntu</a>, 
  <a href='http://www.slackware.com/'>Slackware</a> and 
  <a href='http://www.debian.org'>Debian</a>.
              Hippo CMS is also tested on other systems.  
          </td>
     </tr>


         <tr>
          <td>Support
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/support.png' alt='support icon'/></em> 
   </td>

          <td>Hippo will support running Hippo CMS on all 
              modern <a href='http://www.microsoft.com'>Microsoft</a> Windows 
              and 
              <a href='http://www.linux.org/'>Linux</a> 
              systems:
              <a href='http://www.microsoft.com'>Microsoft</a> Windows: 
              <a href='http://www.microsoft.com/windows/windows-xp/default.aspx'>XP</a>, 
              <a href='http://www.microsoft.com/windows/windows-vista/default.aspx'>Vista</a>, 
              <a href='http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/windowsserver/2000/default.aspx'>2000</a>, 
              <a href='http://www.microsoft.com/windowsserver2003/default.mspx'>Server 2003</a>, etc...
              <a href='http://www.linux.org/'>Linux</a>: 
              <a href='http://www.ubuntu.com/'>Ubuntu</a>, 
              <a href='http://www.debian.org'>Debian</a>, 
              <a href='http://www.slackware.com/'>Slackware</a>, 
              <a href='http://www.redhat.com/'>Redhat</a>, 
              <a href='http://www.novell.com/linux/'>Suse</a>, etc... 
              Support for other
              systems is also possible.
          </td>
    </tr>
    </table>
      </blockquote>
      </subsection>

      <subsection name="Java">

      <blockquote>  
        <table>
         <tr>
          <td>Overall</td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/overall.png' alt='overall icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>
          <a href='http://java.com/en/download/help/'>Sun's Java Virtual Machine</a>, JVM 6 (or 5). 
          The JVM is also called the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) or just Java.
          The Java Development Kit (JDK) contains the JVM.
   </td>
    </tr>
         <tr>
          <td>
           Tested
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/tested.png' alt='Tested icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>Hippo continuously tests Hippo CMS with 
              <a href='http://java.com/en/download/index.jsp'>Java JVM 5 and 6 as 
              supplied by Sun Microsystems</a>. 
          </td>
    </tr>
      <tr>
       <td>
         Acquire
       </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/acquire.png' alt='Acquire icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>      
          Sun's Java JVM 6 (or 5) 
          can be acquired from 
          <a href='http://java.com/en/download/index.jsp'>Sun Microsystems</a>, 
          from websites of Linux distributions 
          (e.g. 
           <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/'>Ubuntu</a>: 
           <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/hardy/sun-java6-jre'>JRE 6</a>
           <a href='http://www.debian.org/distrib/packages'>Debian</a>:
           <a href='http://packages.debian.org/lenny/sun-java6-jre'>JRE 6</a>,
           ) 
          and in other ways. Only packages 
          that ask you to agree to Sun's licence terms contain Java from
          <a href='http://www.sun.com/'>Sun Microsystems</a> and will run the Hippo ECM.
   </td>
      </tr>
    </table>
      </blockquote>

      </subsection>


      <subsection name="Java Servlet Container">

      <blockquote>  
        <table>
         <tr>
          <td>Overall</td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/overall.png' alt='overall icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>Hippo CMS works in any Java Servlet container or Java application server, conforming to version
       <span class='confirm'>2.4</span> of the 
       <a href='http://java.sun.com/products/servlet/reference/api/index.html'>Sun Servlet container 
       specification</a>. 
   </td>
   </tr>
 
         <tr>
          <td>
           Tested
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/tested.png' alt='Tested icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>
              <span class='expires'>Hippo continuously tests Hippo CMS with 
               <a href='http://jetty.mortbay.com/jetty/'>Jetty</a> 6.1
               ,
               <a href='http://tomcat.apache.org/'>Tomcat</a> 6. 
               and 
               <a href='https://glassfish.dev.java.net/public/users.html'>Sun GlassFish</a> V2.
              </span>
          </td>
     </tr>

      <tr>
       <td>
         Acquire
       </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/acquire.png' alt='Acquire icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>    
       Java servlet containers and application servers can be aquired from 
       Apache, Sun, as Linux Packages and from many more sources.   

       E.g.: 
       <a href='http://jetty.mortbay.com/jetty/'>Jetty</a> 6.1
       can be obtained from Hippo: it is included in the
       quickstart-bin package: 
       <a href='../delve_into/quickstart.html'>Quickstart</a>, or
        from codehaus
       <a href='http://docs.codehaus.org/display/JETTY/Downloading+Jetty'>Jetty 6.1 download</a>.          
       <a href="http://tomcat.apache.org/download-60.cgi">Tomcat 6.0 from Apache</a>.
       <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/hardy/glassfishv2'>Linux Ubuntu package of Glassfish V2</a>
       (use apt-get, aptitude or synaptic for easy installation).       
   </td>
      </tr>

</table>
      </blockquote>
      </subsection>


      <subsection name="Relational Database">

      <blockquote>  
        <table>
         <tr>
          <td>Overall</td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/overall.png' alt='overall icon'/></em> 
   </td>
      
   <td>
          Hippo CMS uses a relational database for it's datastorage. By default 
          <a href='http://db.apache.org/derby/'>Apache Derby</a>
          is embedded and configured and runs "out of the box". 
          Hippo CMS can easily be configured to use an other relational database. 
          Possibilities are e.g.:
        <ul>
          <li>MySQL 5.0 and 5.1</li>
          <li>PosgreSQL 8.0 or newer</li>
          <li>Oracle 9.2, 10 and 11</li>
          <li>MS SQLServer 2000 or newer</li>
        </ul>         
   </td>
   </tr>
 
         <tr>
          <td>
           Tested
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/tested.png' alt='Tested icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>Hippo ECM is contineously tested with 
              <a href="http://db.apache.org/derby/">Apache Derby</a> 
              and 
              <a href="http://www.mysql.com">MySQL</a>.
          </td>
    </tr>

    </table>
      </blockquote>

      </subsection>
    </section>
